WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.320 --> 00:00:09.760
There's a fundamental truth about LLMs, large&nbsp;
language models. They are frozen in time. They&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:09.760 --> 00:00:16.000
know everything about our world up until&nbsp;
their training cutoff date and absolutely&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:16.000 --> 00:00:21.680
nothing about what happened 5 minutes ago. Nor&nbsp;
do they know anything about your private data,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:21.680 --> 00:00:28.240
your internal wikis, your proprietary codebase. And&nbsp;
if we do want an LLM to know any of that stuff,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:28.240 --> 00:00:36.000
well, we have to solve the problem of context&nbsp;
injection. How do we get the right data into the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:43.280
model at the right time? And there have been two&nbsp;
very different ways to handle this. Now, the first&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:43.280 --> 00:00:52.000
is really what we can think of as the engineering&nbsp;
approach. It's RAG, retrieval augmented generation.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:52.000 --> 00:01:01.680
So here we've got an LLM and we've also got an&nbsp;
input prompt from the user. Now ahead of time&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:01.680 --> 00:01:09.040
we take some of the documents that we want to give&nbsp;
to this LLM. So these are documents that could be&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:09.040 --> 00:01:19.200
PDFs or code files or entire books and we chunk&nbsp;
them. We break them up into smaller chunks and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:19.200 --> 00:01:27.360
we pass them through to an embedding model and&nbsp;
the embedding model takes those chunks and it&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:27.360 --> 00:01:38.800
turns them into vectors and those vectors are then&nbsp;
stored in a dedicated vector database. Now when a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:38.800 --> 00:01:47.920
user asks a question, it performs a semantic&nbsp;
search to retrieve the most relevant chunks&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:47.920 --> 00:01:54.560
and then inject them into the context window.&nbsp;
So now the context window has the user prompt,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:54.560 --> 00:02:03.360
but it also has all of these chunks that we have&nbsp;
taken from the vector database and together this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:03.360 --> 00:02:10.240
forms the context window. Now this works but&nbsp;
it does rely on something. It relies on the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:10.240 --> 00:02:15.600
hope that your retrieval logic actually found&nbsp;
the right information in the vector database.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:15.600 --> 00:02:23.680
Now the the second approach is really a bit more&nbsp;
of a brute force approach and that one is called&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:23.680 --> 00:02:31.440
long context. Now this is really the model native&nbsp;
solution because you skip the database here and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:31.440 --> 00:02:38.160
you skip the embedding model. All you do is you&nbsp;
take your documents and you just well you put them&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:38.160 --> 00:02:44.400
straight into the context window and then you let&nbsp;
the model's attention mechanism actually do the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:44.400 --> 00:02:50.800
heavy lifting of finding the answer. Now for a&nbsp;
long time this kind of brute force method wasn't&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:50.800 --> 00:02:58.720
really much of an option because initially context&nbsp;
windows were tiny. Early LLMs had context windows&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:58.720 --> 00:03:06.240
that could maybe store what like 4K of tokens.&nbsp;
You couldn't fit a novel in there, let alone a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:06.240 --> 00:03:14.240
corporate knowledge base. You basically had to use&nbsp;
RAG. But today's models have much larger context&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:14.240 --> 00:03:21.840
windows. Some of them have, you know, a million&nbsp;
tokens plus. And to put that into perspective,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:21.840 --> 00:03:29.120
a million tokens is roughly 700,000 words. and you&nbsp;
could fit the entire Lord of the Rings series into&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:29.120 --> 00:03:36.240
the prompt and still have room for The Hobbit. So,&nbsp;
this massive jump in capacity forces us to ask a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:36.240 --> 00:03:43.600
difficult question about our architecture. Because&nbsp;
if we can simply command A, command C, command V,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:43.600 --> 00:03:49.200
all of our documentation into the models context&nbsp;
window, do we really need the overhead of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:49.200 --> 00:03:56.640
embedding models and vector data stores? Is RAG
becoming an unnecessary complexity layer? Well,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:56.640 --> 00:04:03.440
if we accept that we can fit whatever data we&nbsp;
need into the context window, then the argument&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:03.440 --> 00:04:11.520
for doing so basically boils down to one word,&nbsp;
simplicity. And let me give you three reasons why&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:11.520 --> 00:04:20.000
stuffing the context window directly may indeed be&nbsp;
the way to go. And reason number one is collapsing&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:20.000 --> 00:04:27.920
the infrastructure. A production RAG system. Well,&nbsp;
it is quite heavy. You need a a chunking strategy&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:27.920 --> 00:04:33.200
which is like fixed size maybe or sliding window&nbsp;
or recursive. You decide. You're going to need&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:33.200 --> 00:04:39.840
a embedding model to encode the data. You need&nbsp;
a a vector database to store it. You're going&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:39.840 --> 00:04:45.360
to need a reranker to sort the results. you need&nbsp;
to keep all the vectors in sync with your source&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:45.360 --> 00:04:52.800
data. It's basically a lot of moving parts, a lot&nbsp;
of places for things to break. And long context&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:52.800 --> 00:05:01.440
offers what we might call well just simply the uh&nbsp;
the no stack stack. You remove the database, you&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:01.440 --> 00:05:06.880
remove the embeddings, you remove the retrieval&nbsp;
logic. The architecture simplifies down to getting&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:06.880 --> 00:05:15.840
the data and just well sending it to the model. So&nbsp;
that's reason number one. Reason number two is the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:15.840 --> 00:05:23.840
retrieval lottery. Now, RAG introduces a critical&nbsp;
point of failure here, the retrieval step itself,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:23.840 --> 00:05:30.720
because when a user asks a question, RAG looks at&nbsp;
mathematical representations of the data, which are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:30.720 --> 00:05:37.040
stored in vectors. And vectors are basically&nbsp;
just like a really long series of numbers in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:37.040 --> 00:05:43.440
an array. And it tries to find the closest&nbsp;
match. That's semantic search. But semantic&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:43.440 --> 00:05:49.280
search is probabilistic and for all manner of&nbsp;
reasons, the retrieval might fail to find the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:49.280 --> 00:05:55.760
relevant document. And we actually have a name&nbsp;
for this. It's called silent failure. The answer,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:55.760 --> 00:06:01.280
well, it existed in the data, but the LLM never&nbsp;
saw it because the retrieval step didn't return&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:01.280 --> 00:06:08.080
the right results. With long context, there is no&nbsp;
retrieval step. The model gets to see everything.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:08.080 --> 00:06:15.120
Now, reason number three that is well, I think&nbsp;
we're going to call this the whole book problem.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:15.120 --> 00:06:21.200
A RAG is fundamentally designed to retrieve&nbsp;
what exists. It relies on finding a semantic&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:21.200 --> 00:06:27.120
match between your query and a specific snippet&nbsp;
of text in your database. But what if the answer&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:27.120 --> 00:06:35.040
lies in what's not in the database? So, so let's&nbsp;
say you have a set of product requirements stored&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:35.040 --> 00:06:42.960
as a document and you've also got a set of release&nbsp;
notes stored as a document and then we ask which&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:42.960 --> 00:06:50.720
security requirements were omitted from the final&nbsp;
release. Now using RAG when you query for omitted&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:50.720 --> 00:06:57.280
security requirements the vector search looks for&nbsp;
chunks discussing well security and requirements.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:57.280 --> 00:07:02.880
It retrieves snippets from the requirements doc.&nbsp;
It retrieves snippets from the release notes,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:02.880 --> 00:07:09.040
but it cannot retrieve the gap between them. And&nbsp;
because RAG only shows the model a few isolated&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:09.040 --> 00:07:15.280
snapshots, the model never sees the full picture&nbsp;
required to spot the missing pieces. The model&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:15.280 --> 00:07:22.320
really needs both of these documents in full to&nbsp;
perform the comparison, which is exactly what&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:22.320 --> 00:07:28.640
long context does by dumping the whole book, the&nbsp;
full requirements doc and the full release notes&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:28.640 --> 00:07:35.520
into the context window. So, is RAG dead? Is the&nbsp;
vector database destined for the museum of things&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:35.520 --> 00:07:43.600
we needed in 2024? Well, not quite because while&nbsp;
long context wins on simplicity, RAG still has a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:43.600 --> 00:07:53.040
place. And I got another three reasons to support&nbsp;
that. So, reason number one is the rereading text.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:53.040 --> 00:07:59.680
Now, long context creates a massive compute&nbsp;
inefficiency. So, if we take a manual, let's say&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:59.680 --> 00:08:08.000
this is like a a 500 page manual, and we've got to&nbsp;
turn this into tokens. Well, that's something like&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:08.000 --> 00:08:17.120
250k of tokens. And we need to do that every time&nbsp;
we make a user query and we put this document in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:17.120 --> 00:08:23.360
the prompt. You're basically requiring the model&nbsp;
to process that manual every time. Now, RAG also&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:23.360 --> 00:08:30.320
has to process that manual, but it only pays that&nbsp;
processing cost once at indexing time. Now, prompt&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:30.320 --> 00:08:36.160
caching that can partially offset some of this for&nbsp;
static data, but for dynamic data streams where&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:36.160 --> 00:08:45.440
content changes frequently, you are stuck paying&nbsp;
the full tax on every request. Reason number two&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:45.440 --> 00:08:52.560
is the needle in the haystack problem. Now,&nbsp;
there's a an intuitive assumption that if data&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:52.560 --> 00:09:00.160
is in the context window, the model's probably&nbsp;
going to use it, but research suggests otherwise.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:00.160 --> 00:09:06.960
Because as we start with a context window and then&nbsp;
it grows and it continues to grow and now we're at&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:06.960 --> 00:09:14.240
like 500,000 tokens, well, the model's attention&nbsp;
mechanism can get a bit diluted. If you ask a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:14.240 --> 00:09:19.280
specific question about a single paragraph that's&nbsp;
buried in, let's say, the middle of a 2,000 page&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:19.280 --> 00:09:26.000
document, well, the model often fails to retrieve&nbsp;
it or it hallucinates details from the surrounding&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:26.000 --> 00:09:35.200
text. But with RAG, we're giving the model less&nbsp;
noise. So by retrieving, say only the top five&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:35.200 --> 00:09:42.320
relevant chunks, RAG has removed the haystack&nbsp;
and presents the model with just the needles.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:42.320 --> 00:09:49.280
It forces the model to focus on the signal and&nbsp;
not the noise. And then reason number three,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:49.280 --> 00:09:57.200
well that is the infinite data set. Now a context&nbsp;
window of millions of tokens sounds great but in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:57.200 --> 00:10:05.840
the scheme of enterprise data that's really just a&nbsp;
drop in the bucket. I mean an enterprise data lake&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:05.840 --> 00:10:13.840
that's probably measured in terabytes or or maybe&nbsp;
even petabytes. So if you want an infinite data&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:13.840 --> 00:10:19.840
set that stores everything, you really do need to&nbsp;
have a retrieval layer to filter information down&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:19.840 --> 00:10:25.760
to something that fits into the LLM context&nbsp;
window. So where does this leave us? Well,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:25.760 --> 00:10:30.960
if your problem involves a bounded data set and&nbsp;
requires complex global reasoning like analyzing&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:30.960 --> 00:10:38.000
a specific legal contract or summarizing a book, I&nbsp;
think long context is the way to go. It simplifies&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:38.000 --> 00:10:44.000
the stack and it improves the reasoning. But&nbsp;
if you're navigating the infinite data set of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:44.000 --> 00:10:51.280
enterprise knowledge, the vector database remains&nbsp;
the only viable warehouse for your data. But how&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:51.280 --> 00:11:03.440
about you? Are you team long context, team RAG,&nbsp;
maybe a bit of both? Let me know in the comments.

